This code performs a series of steps to load, clean, and analyze the dataset. Here's a breakdown of what each part of the code does:

1. Extracting the ZIP File:¶

  • Zip Extraction: The code extracts a ZIP file (archive.zip) located at C:/Users/lOKITHA/Downloads/ and extracts its contents into a folder named Churn_data.csv.
  • Extracted Files Listing: After extracting, the list of files in the extracted folder is stored in extracted_files.
  • Reading the CSV: The file churn_data.csv is read into a pandas DataFrame (churn_data), which contains the customer churn data.

2. Exploring the Dataset:¶

  • Basic Info: The info() function is used to get a summary of the DataFrame, including the number of non-null entries, data types, and memory usage.
  • First Few Rows: head() is used to preview the first few rows of the dataset, helping you understand its structure (columns and data).

3. Cleaning the 'TotalCharges' Column:¶

  • The TotalCharges column is converted to numeric, using pd.to_numeric(). The errors='coerce' argument ensures that any non-numeric values are converted to NaN.

4. Checking for Missing Values:¶

  • Missing Values: The code checks for missing values in the dataset using isnull().sum(), which returns the number of missing values per column.
  • Handling Missing Data: After identifying missing values, rows with missing values are dropped using dropna(), resulting in churn_data_cleaned.

5. Analyzing the 'Churn' Distribution:¶

  • Churn Distribution: The value_counts(normalize=True) * 100 method calculates the percentage distribution of churn (i.e., how many customers churned vs. did not churn). This helps to check the balance between the churn and non-churn classes.

6. Summary of Cleaned Dataset:¶

  • Cleaned Data Info: After handling missing values, the cleaned dataset's summary is displayed using info() to confirm the shape and data types of the cleaned data.

Outputs:¶

  1. Missing Values: The count of missing values per column before cleaning.
  2. Churn Distribution: The percentage of customers who churned vs. those who did not.
  3. Cleaned Data Info: A summary of the dataset after cleaning, including non-null counts and data types.

  • Data Exploration: Understand the structure of the dataset and identify any issues, like missing or erroneous values.
  • Data Cleaning: Handle missing values and convert data to appropriate types for further analysis.
  • Churn Analysis: Check how imbalanced the churn distribution is and prepare for model building or deeper analysis.

This code visualizes and analyzes churn data using various plots to understand patterns based on different features. Here's a breakdown of each step:

1. Visualize the Churn Distribution:¶

  • Plot Type: countplot from Seaborn.
  • Description: This plot shows the distribution of the Churn column, which indicates whether a customer churned (1) or not (0). The count of customers who churned versus those who did not is visualized.
  • Purpose: Helps to see if the dataset is balanced or imbalanced in terms of churn.

2. Analyze Churn Based on Contract Type:¶

  • Plot Type: countplot with hue based on the Churn column.
  • Description: This plot visualizes churn distribution across different contract types (e.g., month-to-month, one-year, two-year). The hue='Churn' argument separates the counts by churn status.
  • Purpose: Reveals if customers with certain contract types are more likely to churn, helping identify which contract types may correlate with higher churn rates.

3. Analyze Churn Based on Tenure (Categorized):¶

  • Plot Type: countplot with the TenureGroup column (which is created by binning the tenure column into 6 groups based on months).
  • Description: The TenureGroup divides the customers' tenure into different ranges (e.g., 0-12 months, 13-24 months, etc.), and churn is visualized for each group.
  • Purpose: Helps to identify if there’s a relationship between a customer’s tenure (how long they've been with the company) and their likelihood to churn.

4. Analyze Churn Based on Payment Method:¶

  • Plot Type: countplot with the PaymentMethod column on the y-axis.
  • Description: This plot shows the churn distribution based on different payment methods (e.g., electronic check, mailed check, etc.), with churn separated by color.
  • Purpose: Identifies if certain payment methods correlate with higher churn rates, which may indicate customer preferences or dissatisfaction.

Common Elements:¶

  • Style: The Seaborn style whitegrid is used for clear and clean visualizations.
  • Palette: The viridis color palette is used to differentiate between churn (yes/no) in each plot.
  • Legends: Each plot has a legend to indicate churn status (typically "Churn" and "No Churn").

General Purpose:¶

The plots provide insights into how different customer features (e.g., contract type, tenure, payment method) relate to churn behavior, which can guide further analysis or model feature selection. These visualizations are useful for identifying key factors influencing churn.

DATA PREPROCESSING:-¶

This code performs preprocessing on a dataset (churn_data_cleaned), including converting categorical variables to numerical values and normalizing numerical features. Here's a breakdown:

  1. One-Hot Encoding for Categorical Variables:

    • categorical_columns selects columns with object data types (i.e., categorical variables), excluding the 'customerID' column.
    • pd.get_dummies() converts the categorical columns to binary (0/1) columns, using one-hot encoding, while drop_first=True avoids multicollinearity by dropping the first category in each column.

  2. Normalization of Numerical Features:

    • MinMaxScaler() scales the specified numerical columns (tenure, MonthlyCharges, TotalCharges) to a range between 0 and 1, ensuring features are on the same scale, which is often required for machine learning algorithms.

  3. Summary of the Preprocessed Data:

    • churn_data_encoded.info() prints a summary of the dataset, showing the data types and non-null counts.

  4. Preview of the Preprocessed Data:

    • churn_data_encoded.head() shows the first five rows of the transformed dataset to give a preview of the changes.

This code transforms categorical data and scales numerical features to prepare the dataset for further analysis or modeling.

import pandas as pd
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler

# Step 1: Convert categorical variables to numerical (One-Hot Encoding)
# Exclude 'customerID' since it's a unique identifier for each customer
categorical_columns = churn_data_cleaned.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns.drop('customerID')
# Drop the 'customerID' column from the DataFrame
churn_data_cleaned = churn_data_cleaned.drop(columns=['customerID'])

# Verify the column is removed
print(churn_data_cleaned.head())

# Perform one-hot encoding
churn_data_encoded = pd.get_dummies(churn_data_cleaned, columns=categorical_columns, drop_first=True)

# Step 2: Normalize the numerical columns
# Initialize the Min-Max Scaler
scaler = MinMaxScaler()

# Numerical columns to normalize
numerical_columns = ['tenure', 'MonthlyCharges', 'TotalCharges']

# Normalize the numerical columns
churn_data_encoded[numerical_columns] = scaler.fit_transform(churn_data_encoded[numerical_columns])

# Step 3: Summary of the preprocessed dataset
print("Preprocessed Dataset Summary:")
print(churn_data_encoded.info())

# Step 4: Preview the preprocessed data
print("\nPreview of Preprocessed Dataset:")
print(churn_data_encoded.head())

# Example: data = pd.read_csv("churn_data.csv")

# Features (X) and target variable (y)
X = churn_data_encoded.drop(columns=['Churn_Yes'])  # Replace 'Churn' with the actual target column name

# Splitting the data into training, validation, and testing sets
# First split into train+validation and test
X_train_val, X_test, y_train_val, y_test = train_test_split(
    X, y, test_size=0.15, stratify=y, random_state=42
)

# Next, split train+validation into training and validation sets
X_train, X_val, y_train, y_val = train_test_split(
    X_train_val, y_train_val, test_size=0.15 / 0.85, stratify=y_train_val, random_state=42
)

# Display the shapes of the splits
print("Training Set:", X_train.shape, y_train.shape)
print("Validation Set:", X_val.shape, y_val.shape)
print("Testing Set:", X_test.shape, y_test.shape)

MODEL SELECTION¶

Baseline Models: Start with simple models like Logistic Regression for interpretability. Advanced Models: Experiment with more complex models such as: Decision Trees Random Forests Gradient Boosting (e.g., XGBoost, LightGBM, CatBoost) Support Vector Machines (SVM) Neural Networks

# Import necessary libraries
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier, GradientBoostingClassifier
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.svm import SVC
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score

# Assuming X_train, X_val, y_train, y_val are already defined
# Example for creating the splits (uncomment if needed):
# X_train, X_val, y_train, y_val = train_test_split(
#     X, y, test_size=0.15, stratify=y, random_state=42
# )

# Ensure y_train and y_val are 1D arrays to avoid warnings
y_train = y_train.values.ravel()  # Convert to 1D
y_val = y_val.values.ravel()      # Convert to 1D

# Define the models to evaluate
models = {
    "Logistic Regression": LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000, random_state=42),
    "Random Forest": RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42),
    "SVM (Support Vector Machine)": SVC(probability=True, random_state=42),
    "Gradient Boosting": GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=42),
}

# Evaluate models
results = {}

for model_name, model in models.items():
    # Train the model
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    # Predict on validation set
    y_val_pred = model.predict(X_val)
    
    # Calculate metrics
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_val, y_val_pred)
    precision = precision_score(y_val, y_val_pred, pos_label=1)
    recall = recall_score(y_val, y_val_pred, pos_label=1)
    f1 = f1_score(y_val, y_val_pred, pos_label=1)
    
    # Store results
    results[model_name] = {
        "Accuracy": accuracy,
        "Precision": precision,
        "Recall": recall,
        "F1-Score": f1,
    }

# Print results
print("Model Selection Results:")
for model_name, metrics in results.items():
    print(f"\n{model_name}:")
    for metric, value in metrics.items():
        print(f"  {metric}: {value:.4f}")

# Select the best model based on F1-Score
best_model = max(results, key=lambda x: results[x]["F1-Score"])
print(f"\nBest Model: {best_model}")

hypermeter tuning¶

Understanding the Components fit()

Purpose: Learns the parameters or characteristics of the data. Example: In scaling, it calculates the mean and standard deviation of the data. transform()

Purpose: Applies the learned parameters to transform the data. Example: In scaling, it uses the calculated mean and standard deviation to scale the data. fit_transform()

Combines the above two steps into one method. Used when you want to both learn from the data and transform it in a single step.

What is Hyperparameter Tuning? Hyperparameter tuning is the process of finding the optimal combination of hyperparameters for a machine learning model to improve its performance. Hyperparameters are the settings or configurations of a model that must be set before training begins (e.g., the learning rate, number of trees in a Random Forest, or kernel in SVM).

Unlike model parameters, which are learned during training (e.g., weights in a neural network), hyperparameters are set manually or tuned using automated techniques.

#1.random Search:-
from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV
from scipy.stats import randint

# Define parameter distributions
param_dist = {
    'n_estimators': randint(100, 500),        # Random integers between 100 and 500
    'max_depth': [None, 10, 20, 30],          # Predefined depths
    'min_samples_split': randint(2, 20),      # Random integers between 2 and 20
    'min_samples_leaf': randint(1, 10),       # Random integers between 1 and 10
}

# Initialize the model
rf_model = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)

# Perform Randomized Search
random_search = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=rf_model, param_distributions=param_dist, 
                                   scoring='f1', n_iter=50, cv=5, verbose=2, random_state=42, n_jobs=-1)
random_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Best parameters and score
print("Best Parameters from Random Search:", random_search.best_params_)
print("Best F1-Score from Random Search:", random_search.best_score_)

# Evaluate on validation set
best_rf_model = random_search.best_estimator_
y_val_pred = best_rf_model.predict(X_val)
f1 = f1_score(y_val, y_val_pred, pos_label=1)
print("F1-Score on Validation Set with Best Model:", f1)

    'n_estimators': [100, 200, 300],   # Number of trees in the forest
    'max_depth': [None, 10, 20, 30],  # Maximum depth of the tree
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],  # Minimum samples required to split a node
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4],    # Minimum samples required at each leaf node

Adress class impbalance¶

  1. Class imbalance occurs when one class significantly outnumbers the other, leading to biased predictions favoring the majority class.
  2. Oversampling (e.g., SMOTE) creates synthetic samples for the minority class, while undersampling reduces majority class samples.
  3. Class weight adjustment assigns higher penalties for misclassifying the minority class, supported in models like Random Forest and Logistic Regression.
  4. Cost-sensitive learning modifies algorithms to prioritize the minority class during training.
  5. Ensemble techniques like BalancedRandomForestClassifier handle imbalanced datasets effectively.
  6. Evaluation metrics such as Precision, Recall, F1-Score, and ROC-AUC are better suited for imbalanced data than accuracy.
  7. Combining these methods ensures robust performance and fair predictions for the minority class.

CODE explanation:- This code snippet demonstrates how to use SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique) to balance an imbalanced dataset by oversampling the minority class in the training data. Here's what each part does:

Code Breakdown:¶

  1. Import SMOTE:
    from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE imports the SMOTE module from the imblearn library.

  2. Initialize SMOTE:
    smote = SMOTE(random_state=42) creates an instance of SMOTE with a fixed random seed for reproducibility.

  3. Apply SMOTE to Training Data:
    X_train_balanced, y_train_balanced = smote.fit_resample(X_train, y_train):

    • fit_resample learns the data distribution from X_train and y_train and generates synthetic samples for the minority class.
    • The balanced data is stored in X_train_balanced and y_train_balanced.

  4. Check Class Distribution:
    print(pd.Series(y_train_balanced).value_counts()) displays the count of each class in the new, balanced training set.

Expected Output Example:¶

Before SMOTE:

Class Distribution:
0    4000
1     500

After SMOTE:

Class Distribution After SMOTE:
0    4000
1    4000

Key Benefits:¶

  • SMOTE avoids simply duplicating minority class samples by generating synthetic data.
  • Helps models better learn patterns for the minority class, improving metrics like Recall and F1-Score.

Deployment Preparation and Post-Deployment Monitoring¶

1. Deployment Preparation¶

Deployment involves making your model available for real-world use, often as a web service or API. It requires a few key steps to ensure that your model performs well in production.

Key Steps for Deployment Preparation:¶

  1. Model Exporting:

    • Save the trained model to a file so it can be loaded in the deployment environment.
    • Common formats:
      • Pickle (joblib or pickle in Python)
      • ONNX (Open Neural Network Exchange)
    • Example:
      import joblib
joblib.dump(model, 'churn_model.pkl')

  2. Creating a Service/Endpoint:

    • Use frameworks like Flask, FastAPI, or Django to wrap your model into a REST API.

    • Example (Flask):

      from flask import Flask, request, jsonify
import joblib

app = Flask(__name__)
model = joblib.load('churn_model.pkl')

@app.route('/predict', methods=['POST'])
def predict():
    data = request.get_json()
    prediction = model.predict([data['features']])
    return jsonify(prediction.tolist())

if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(debug=True)

  3. Containerization:

    • Use Docker to containerize the model and the application to ensure consistency across different environments.
    • Dockerfile:
      FROM python:3.8-slim
COPY . /app
WORKDIR /app
RUN pip install -r requirements.txt
CMD ["python", "app.py"]

  4. Scalability & Load Balancing:

    • Use Kubernetes or cloud services (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure Functions) to scale your application.
    • Ensure that your deployment architecture can handle high traffic if necessary.

  5. Environment Considerations:

    • Ensure the environment for deployment has the necessary software dependencies, such as Python libraries, server configurations, etc.
    • Set up version control for the code and model (e.g., using Git, Model Versioning Tools).

2. Post-Deployment Monitoring¶

After deployment, continuous monitoring is essential to track the model’s performance and ensure that it continues to provide value.

Key Areas for Post-Deployment Monitoring:¶

  1. Model Performance Monitoring:

    • Accuracy: Regularly track model accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score, etc., to ensure it meets performance expectations.
    • Data Drift: Monitor for any significant changes in the data distribution (i.e., input features) over time.
      • Tools: Evidently AI, WhyLabs to track data and model performance over time.
      • Action: Retrain the model periodically or trigger automatic retraining if necessary.

  2. Model Monitoring Tools:

    • Use specialized tools for tracking model health, latency, and throughput.
      • MLflow, Kubeflow, TensorFlow Serving for managing and serving models.
      • Prometheus and Grafana for system performance monitoring.

  3. Error Tracking and Logging:

    • Log model predictions, input data, and errors.
    • Use logging tools (e.g., Logstash, Sentry) to capture anomalies and model failures.

  4. Feedback Loops:

    • Incorporate user or system feedback on model predictions to identify any wrong predictions or issues in real-time.
    • Use feedback to fine-tune the model or trigger retraining.

  5. Alerts and Notifications:

    • Set up alerts for abnormal behavior such as:
      • Model performance drops below a threshold.
      • Inference time is higher than expected.
      • High error rates.
    • Use Slack, email notifications, or PagerDuty for timely alerts.

  6. Retraining and Model Updates:

    • Plan a retraining strategy based on performance monitoring, especially if the model is showing signs of degradation (concept drift).
    • Automated retraining can be set up through tools like Kubeflow Pipelines, AWS SageMaker, etc.

  7. A/B Testing:

    • Use A/B testing to compare different model versions and observe which performs better in the production environment.
    • Gradually roll out new versions and monitor their impact.
